<BaseLayout title="Kazakhstan in 60 seconds" description="A concise starting point for understanding modern Kazakhstan without reducing it to a stereotype.">
  <article class="wrap-wide start-page">
    <header class="page-hero"><p class="eyebrow">Start here</p><h1>Kazakhstan in 60 seconds.</h1><p class="lead">A sovereign Central Asian country with its own history, state language and diverse modern society—not a film set, not a Russian region and not a single landscape.</p></header>
    <section class="fact-grid fact-grid--wide">
      <article><span>01</span><h2>A country, not a cultural shortcut</h2><p>Kazakhstan has been independent since 1991 and is a United Nations member state.</p><a href="/myths/part-of-russia">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>02</span><h2>Kazakh is not Russian</h2><p>Kazakh is a Turkic language. Russian belongs to the Indo-European family. Both are widely present, but they are not the same language.</p><a href="/myths/kazakh-and-russian">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>03</span><h2>Tradition is not everyday housing</h2><p>The yurt is living cultural heritage and an important symbol. Most residents live in urban or conventional permanent housing.</p><a href="/myths/yurts">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>04</span><h2>More than one landscape</h2><p>Steppe and desert are real parts of Kazakhstan, alongside mountains, lakes, wetlands, forests and large cities.</p><a href="/myths/only-steppe">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>05</span><h2>130+ nationalities, not one</h2><p>Ethnic Kazakhs make up roughly 70 percent of the population. More than 130 nationalities officially reside in Kazakhstan, including Russians, Uzbeks, Uyghurs, Germans, Koreans and others.</p><a href="/myths/ethnic-diversity">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>06</span><h2>Not only oil</h2><p>Hydrocarbons are significant but Kazakhstan also produces more uranium than any other country and exports metals, grain and financial services.</p><a href="/myths/economy-oil">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>07</span><h2>Borat is fiction, not a portrait</h2><p>The film uses Kazakhstan as a backdrop for British satire. The country shown bears no factual resemblance to the real one.</p><a href="/myths/borat">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>08</span><h2>The capital is Astana, not Almaty</h2><p>Kazakhstan moved its capital from Almaty to a new northern city in 1997. That city is now called Astana. Almaty remains the largest city.</p><a href="/myths/capital-astana">Check the evidence →</a></article>
      <article><span>09</span><h2>No nuclear weapons since 1995</h2><p>Kazakhstan inherited the world's fourth-largest nuclear arsenal in 1991 and voluntarily gave up every warhead by 1995, joining the Non-Proliferation Treaty as a non-nuclear state.</p><a href="/myths/nuclear-weapons">Check the evidence →</a></article>
    </section>
    <section class="context-callout"><p class="eyebrow">The useful rule</p><h2>When a reference is entertaining, ask whether it is also evidence.</h2><p>Comedy, memes and tourism clips can be entry points. They are not substitutes for sources about real people, language, history or institutions.</p><a class="btn btn--primary" href="/myths">Open the evidence library</a></section>
